<article>
    <h1>Rays of hope shine through the gloom</h1>
    <h2>De&#xAD;spite curbs, Christ&#xAD;mas is marked with ri&#xAD;tu&#xAD;als and rev&#xAD;er&#xAD;ence around the world</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201227/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-27"><time>2020-12-27</time></a>
        - <span>WORLD</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>•</p>
    <p>Christ­mas falls on one of the dark­est days of the year, com­ing soon af­ter the win­ter sol­stice. This year, it also came dur­ing a dark time for hu­man­ity amid a world­wide vi­ral pan­demic.</p>
    <p>“Here we are, cel­e­brat­ing Christ­mas, yet de­prived of the greet­ings, hugs, kisses and hand­shakes that nor­mally fill this day,” Car­di­nal Vin­cent Ni­chols, arch­bishop of West­min­ster, said dur­ing a mid­night Mass in a nearly empty West­min­ster Cathe­dral in Lon­don.</p>
    <p>“In the dark­ness of this pan­demic, so many of our com­fort­able as­sump­tions are be­ing shaken.”</p>
    <p>Yet the cer­e­monies went on, of­ten broad­cast on tele­vi­sion or, as with the West­min­ster Mass, streamed on­line.</p>
    <p>If the pan­demic has de­prived wor­ship­pers of com­mu­nity, these lonely acts of faith may have shed a bit of light in the dark­ness.</p>
    <p>At the cathe­dral of Notre Dame in Paris, which was nearly de­stroyed by fire last year, the annual Christ­mas Eve cho­ral con­cert took place with­out an au­di­ence and with the me­di­ae­val ed­i­fice still un­der re­con­struc­tion.</p>
    <p>The choir, or­gan­ist and cel­list, all so­cially dis­tanced, wore hard hats and pro­tec­tive cov­er­alls.</p>
    <p>At St Reinold’s Church in Dort­mund, Ger­many, or­gan­ist Gerd von der Heyde poured out his heart to the build­ing’s 13th-cen­tury stone walls.</p>
    <p>At Yoido Full Gospel Church in Seoul, South Korea, the min­is­ter preached to empty pews and an on­line con­gre­ga­tion.</p>
    <p>At Church of the Nativity in Beth­le­hem, on the spot where Chris­tians be­lieve Je­sus was born, mid­night Mass is usu­ally the so­cial event of the year.</p>
    <p>This year, the ser­vice was lim­ited to a few church of­fi­cials, diplo­mats and Beth­le­hem’s mayor.</p>
    <p>Tens of thou­sands of Ro­man Catholics usu­ally pack St Peter’s Square i n the Vatican for the Pope’s annual Christ­mas ad­dress.</p>
    <p>This year, with Italy un­der lock­down, the square was closed.</p>
    <p>Pope Fran­cis, speak­ing from a lectern in­side the Apos­tolic Palace, said the pan­demic should com­pel peo­ple to re­flect on their com­mon hu­man­ity, and that un­der­stand­ing should guide how vac­cines are dis­trib­uted.</p>
    <p>“I beg ev­ery­one, heads of state, com­pa­nies and in­ter­na­tional or­gan­i­sa­tions, to pro­mote co­op­er­a­tion and not com­pe­ti­tion, to find a so­lu­tion for ev­ery­one, vac­cines for all, es­pe­cially for the most vul­ner­a­ble and needy in all ar­eas of the planet,” he added.</p>
    <p>While the pan­demic has cre­ated un­told hard­ship for mil­lions this year, it has also in many places brought out the best in peo­ple.</p>
    <p>“Have we not seen these months of difficulty marked by count­less acts of ran­dom kind­ness, quiet hero­ism, self­less ser­vice, re­mark­able com­mu­nity ef­forts, all di­rected to­wards those most i n need?” Car­di­nal Ni­chols asked in his ser­mon at West­min­ster.</p>
    <p>Such acts, he said, had “pen­e­trated the dark­ness”.</p>

